EN IWAMURA: 25 minutes online advice 
Open to everyone with internet access

March 2020 @eniwamura 
Starting price AUD 100.00
100% donate to Wildlife Rescue Emergency Fund

En Iwamura was born in Kyoto, Japan in 1988. His interest in art started with having two painters as parents. When applying to art school in Japan, where he earned his BFA and first MFA at the Kanazawa College of Art and Craft, he first thought he would follow their path but instead chose ceramics as a medium. This three-dimensional choice allows him to experiment with the viewer's experience of occupying space concurrently with his work. He references this relationship between negative space, viewer, and object back to the Japanese philosophy of Ma. Finding the most comfortable Ma between people, places, or objects can create a specific relationship with that person, place or object relative to an exact moment in time. More than just being three-dimensional, clay is also in itself a very historic medium, which helps Iwamura further explore his interest of specific moments in time.

En Iwamura describes his work as “three-dimensional clay doodling”. Incorporating layers of slip, underglaze and glaze drawings, his handbuilt ceramic sculptures draw attention from art collectors around the world.
In 2016, he received a second MFA at Clemson University in South Carolina. En has exhibited both nationally and internationally in New York City, Seattle, WA, Kansas City, MO, Durham, NC, Japan, Canada, China and more. En is currently working at Shigaraki ceramic cultural park, Japan.

With his extensive experience or living in two cultures and dealing with contemporary art gallery and art fairs, En could offer valuable advice on many topics – technical, artist style, dealing with commercial galleries, how to build large-scale work, working with space as well as how to negotiate your life and draw inspiration from two different cultures.

The winning bid will have the chance to get feedback and answers to help with their work. The session will last up to 25 mins.
The auctions will close on Friday 31 January at 8.30pm, AEST (Melbourne time). PLEASE BID ON FA
